    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my flight theory exam. can u explain what actually causes clear air turbulence (CAT) and why it's so hard for pilots to spot on the radar?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Clear Air Turbulence (CAT) is caused by air masses with different density and temperature that can create pockets of turbulent air, often miles above the ground. This type of turbulence forms when warm air rises rapidly, cooler air sinks, and air pockets are created along the boundaries of these air masses. CAT is difficult to spot on radar because it typically occurs in areas with limited radar coverage, and the turbulent pockets are not intense or sustained long enough to show up on radar, making them invisible. Additionally, CAT often forms in altitudes where radar signals are weaker and often outside the primary radar scan bands.",
      "source": "target",
