    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so it's basically just because the air is moving weirdly due to temperature changes? is there anything specific about the jet stream that makes the turbulence more intense or unpredictable?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the unusual air motion due to temperature changes is the main cause of CAT. The jet stream, a fast-moving band of air typically found in the upper atmosphere, can contribute to the intensity and unpredictability of turbulence. Its complex and unstable motion can create areas of rotation, updrafts, and other wind shear conditions that contribute to the formation of CAT. These shear elements can be difficult to predict using traditional weather forecasting tools, making CAT more challenging for pilots to anticipate and navigate.",
      "source": "target",
